metadata.name: Galdricge #95
metadata.description:
Galdricge, meaning 'Enchantress' in Anglo-Saxon, is an attempt to evoke a sense of grace and femininity from stark, abstract elements. 


Add "&png" to querystring for 2048x2048 png export 
Add "&svg" for svg export. There are up to 5 layers which can be controlled in Inkscape for different pen widths and colours 


This work is plottable thanks to open-sourced code and article from twilliability. Check out his plotter pieces at https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/twilliability  
Article : https://jealousmarkup.xyz/texts/webgl-line-hiding 
Code : https://gist.github.com/gugray/dfdbef073a3efe1abb5f501728ac9d51 


Other libs (refer console output for license info) 
Graphics : PIXIJS https://github.com/pixijs/pixijs 
Geometry : JSTS https://github.com/bjornharrtell/jsts 
Noise : SIMPLEX-NOISE https://github.com/jwagner/simplex-noise.js 
Random number lib : Fdrandom.js https://github.com/strainer/fdrandom.js 


Made on and off, over 5 months of the great 2023 bear market.

metadata.name: Ōmukade #58
metadata.description:
Dance of many legs. Moving fast knows that nothing can forever last. For if it stops, it meets its end, no pause allowed.

- P: Screenshot

metadata.name: Backyard #91
metadata.description:
The house I lived in when I was young was a house with a small backyard with brick walls. I often imagined it in the backyard at the time.
If I grow up and have my own house later, I want to live in a house with a backyard with a dense nature and a view of a vast mountain.
Although I haven't achieved the imagination that I did when I was young yet. I'm so happy because I think it came true in the world of generative art.
I hope you have the backyard that you imagine.

--

Features:
 - Canvas: vertical / horizontal
 - Palette: black / red / green / purple / yellow / blue
 - Highlighted object: tree / flowers / brickwall
 - MountainType: standard / sharp
 - Tree: true / false
 - Flowers: true / false
 - Stars: true / false
 - Fog: true / false
 - Brickwall: true / false
 - Sun or Moon: true / false / supersize
 - After the rain: true / false

--

Press "s" in live mode to download the rendered image as a png file. (2000 x 3000 for vertical, 3000 x 1500 for horizontal)

Made with p5js and passion
By thion, September 2023

metadata.name: Hexscape #10
metadata.description:
The hex is a place to play. 

This work draws on a number of inspirations. The hexagonal columnar formations that igneous rock can form. Places where rock conforms to nature's laws and unwittingly generates a pleasing landscape. And on the hex grids of the tabletop games that I used to spend hours pushing miniatures around on. This kind of landscape evokes, for me, possibilities for play and enjoyment, where it is always possible that something new and unexpected may be discovered. So I have created rules that I hope may generate something that inspires those feelings.

Features:
Hex Size: 20, 30, 50 or 70
Palette: Twenty one possible palettes.
Aspect Ratio: 1:1.2, 1:1.6, 1.6:1


The work will initially render with a short edge of 1000 pixels. 

Controls:
[1] Set shortest edge to 1000 pixels.
[2] Set shortest edge to 2000 pixels.
[3] Set shortest edge to 4000 pixels.
[s] Save at current resolution.


Made with javascript and p5.js. Simplex noise provided by OpenSimplexNoise.js.

metadata.name: Scythe of Atropos #15
metadata.description:
Scythe of Atropos: A Moiraic sister piece to ‘Filigree of Lachesis’ and ‘Braiding of Clotho’.

“‘Tis true. There's magic in the web of it.”

A random walker emerges from the central void, disgorging ellipse and rectangle with the certainty of Perlin noise. Hue plays a greater part in this piece, and whitespace forms beneath the delicate tracework of thin black lines. A dance of rectangles swirl around the central point, interspersed with elliptical forms.

Rendering is complete after a certain number of frames, at which point a high-resolution png can be exported by pressing 's'.

Features vary in rarity, and affect weighting, size, colour and density of stroke.

Entropy is high.

metadata.name: Alma de Flor #18
metadata.description:
Alma de Flor is a project inspired by nature and floral afterlife. 

Plants are alive, they grow on our planet and populate almost every continent on earth. 
They live, grow and die. 
Some plants live a long time, some others don't. Kind of like humans, they change and evolve. They have souls, but they're different from ours, they differ in energy. 

Living in a tropical country allowed me to live in a place with huge biodiversity, so for me, this is how a born European, raised Latino person connects with this feeling.

metadata.name: The View #60
Blooming dancers #92
metadata.description:
Inspired by the similarity between a dancer's dress and a blooming flower.

It's an homage to art and nature, with exclusive features including :

- A choice between 12 modern and 12 rarer Artist inspired color palettes (Thanks to http://www.colorlisa.com/)
- 1 to 5 dancers
- Various Soft and Hard framing options
- A unique full canvas system which allows the collector to display on portrait, landscape or square screen the art
- A lot of line and background style variations.

The art is better viewed in full screen, captures don't display the fine details

patxol - 2022

Made with p5js
